but it isn't whether or not human existence actually matters that's central to his work.

215
00:16:00,660 --> 00:16:04,180
It's not quite the idea of that stuff actually being true,

216
00:16:04,660 --> 00:16:10,260
but rather the direct feeling of being unimportant in the grand scheme of things.

217
00:16:10,260 --> 00:16:14,020
Lovecraft's writing and tropes function in this regard a lot like one of the writers

218
00:16:14,020 --> 00:16:16,820
who in turn inspired him, Edgar Allan Poe.

219
00:16:16,820 --> 00:16:19,540
Poe doesn't exactly make people feel good.

220
00:16:19,540 --> 00:16:22,900
Rather, he makes them feel sad in a productive way.

221
00:16:22,900 --> 00:16:26,580
It can make people who are prone to those feelings feel less alone

222
00:16:26,580 --> 00:16:29,140
because they know others have them too.

223
00:16:29,140 --> 00:16:33,380
The Call of Cthulhu doesn't begin by telling you how scary a big monster could be

224
00:16:33,380 --> 00:16:36,580
or giving you a description of what its tentacles would look like.

225
00:16:36,580 --> 00:16:41,380
It opens with a profound fear of the future and of what discoveries might lie there.

226
00:16:41,380 --> 00:16:46,180
The sciences, each straining in its own direction, have hitherto harmed us little,

227
00:16:46,180 --> 00:16:48,980
but someday the piecing together of dissociated knowledge

228
00:16:48,980 --> 00:16:53,860
will open up such terrifying vistas of reality and of our frightful position therein

229
00:16:53,860 --> 00:16:56,500
that we shall either go mad from the revelation

230
00:16:56,500 --> 00:17:01,140
or flee from the deadly light into the peace and safety of a new dark age.

231
00:17:01,220 --> 00:17:04,820
So what mattered wasn't how creative or imaginative his stories got,

232
00:17:04,820 --> 00:17:08,180
but how they related to people's own feelings of unimportance

233
00:17:08,180 --> 00:17:10,580
then and now in the actual world.

234
00:17:10,580 --> 00:17:13,620
There's the old joke that a paranoid person,

235
00:17:13,620 --> 00:17:16,500
if they were ever to discover the room that the government spied on them from

236
00:17:16,500 --> 00:17:18,260
with all the notes on their lives,

237
00:17:18,260 --> 00:17:21,460
they wouldn't actually be any more afraid because of this.

238
00:17:21,460 --> 00:17:23,220
They'd feel validated.

239
00:17:23,220 --> 00:17:24,740
They weren't paranoid.

240
00:17:24,740 --> 00:17:25,860
They were right.

241
00:17:25,860 --> 00:17:29,780
And through that lens, Lovecraft is a way of feeling completely assured

242
00:17:29,780 --> 00:17:32,740
that the world really is out to get you,

243
00:17:32,740 --> 00:17:36,340
and maybe God doesn't care or hates you or wants you dead.

244
00:17:36,340 --> 00:17:38,740
You can use special effects to design something scarier

245
00:17:38,740 --> 00:17:40,820
than the man himself could ever have imagined,

246
00:17:40,820 --> 00:17:44,820
but that alone isn't actually the thing that's scary about the story.

247
00:17:44,820 --> 00:17:47,940
What's scary is the way these smaller aspects build

248
00:17:47,940 --> 00:17:52,020
to create a sense that humans are tiny and powerless creatures,

249
00:17:52,020 --> 00:17:54,340
that the greatest height we can aspire to

250
00:17:54,340 --> 00:17:59,700
is a deep and intimate understanding of just how little we understand.

251
00:17:59,700 --> 00:18:02,740
Lovecraft rarely reused his creations between stories,

252
00:18:02,740 --> 00:18:06,980
and that's because the creatures he came up with didn't really matter.

253
00:18:06,980 --> 00:18:08,820
They were interchangeable,

254
00:18:08,820 --> 00:18:11,380
and the ideas they existed to communicate

255
00:18:11,380 --> 00:18:14,340
with their scope and alienness was what mattered.

256
00:18:14,340 --> 00:18:19,060
Unfortunately, however, this is where things get a bit hairy and complicated.

257
00:18:19,060 --> 00:18:21,380
One of Lovecraft's most famous quotes goes,

258
00:18:21,380 --> 00:18:24,420
"'The oldest and strongest emotion of mankind is fear,

259
00:18:24,420 --> 00:18:28,500
and the oldest and strongest kind of fear is fear of the unknown.'"

260
00:18:28,500 --> 00:18:30,500
And you know what this guy didn't know much about?

261
00:18:31,140 --> 00:18:33,380
People of other races.

262
00:18:33,380 --> 00:18:35,780
Look, we've managed to brush past it,

263
00:18:35,780 --> 00:18:40,580
but we do have to talk about Lovecraft's racism, sexism,

264
00:18:41,460 --> 00:18:43,780
antisemitism, and homophobia.

265
00:18:45,460 --> 00:18:46,500
It's happening now.

266
00:18:47,780 --> 00:18:51,460
So for the folks out there who don't think you can criticize an author's beliefs

267
00:18:51,460 --> 00:18:54,900
just because it was a different time and it happened 100 years ago,

268
00:18:55,460 --> 00:18:56,500
thanks for watching.

