00:27:20,900 --> 00:27:22,580
much of a comparison with Lovecraft

476
00:27:22,580 --> 00:27:23,940
in a straightforward viewing,

477
00:27:24,580 --> 00:27:26,500
but maybe that's proof

478
00:27:26,500 --> 00:27:27,780
of how good it is.

479
00:27:27,780 --> 00:27:29,220
The Shape of Water has

480
00:27:29,220 --> 00:27:30,820
so successfully excavated

481
00:27:30,820 --> 00:27:32,020
all the garbage away

482
00:27:32,020 --> 00:27:33,540
from its spiritual predecessor

483
00:27:33,540 --> 00:27:34,900
that despite depicting something

484
00:27:34,900 --> 00:27:36,260
that directly happened

485
00:27:36,260 --> 00:27:37,460
in a story del Toro

486
00:27:37,460 --> 00:27:38,420
has definitely read,

487
00:27:38,980 --> 00:27:41,780
the comparison still feels strange,

488
00:27:41,780 --> 00:27:43,060
wrong almost.

489
00:27:43,060 --> 00:27:45,380
This film captures the beautiful,

490
00:27:45,380 --> 00:27:47,460
human, mesmerizing center

491
00:27:47,460 --> 00:27:48,820
of Lovecraft's writing.

492
00:27:48,820 --> 00:27:50,580
It's the kind of story he could,

493
00:27:51,220 --> 00:27:52,740
or perhaps should,

494
00:27:52,740 --> 00:27:54,340
have been writing all along.

495
00:27:54,340 --> 00:27:55,540
For me, there's something

496
00:27:55,540 --> 00:27:56,980
personally wonderful about

497
00:27:56,980 --> 00:27:58,260
finally really coming to

498
00:27:58,260 --> 00:27:59,380
an understanding of a film

499
00:27:59,380 --> 00:28:00,340
that touched me in ways

500
00:28:00,340 --> 00:28:01,220
I didn't realize

501
00:28:01,220 --> 00:28:02,340
and that never really

502
00:28:02,340 --> 00:28:03,780
got much recognition.

503
00:28:03,780 --> 00:28:05,380
Right as a film that understands

504
00:28:05,380 --> 00:28:06,820
this just as well gets released

505
00:28:06,820 --> 00:28:08,580
and actually gets major recognition

506
00:28:08,580 --> 00:28:09,700
and even wins an Oscar.

507
00:28:10,100 --> 00:28:11,540
I am an immigrant,

508
00:28:11,540 --> 00:28:13,220
unlike many, many of you,

509
00:28:13,220 --> 00:28:15,300
and in the last 25 years,

510
00:28:15,300 --> 00:28:16,980
I've been living in a country

511
00:28:16,980 --> 00:28:17,940
all of our own,

512
00:28:17,940 --> 00:28:18,740
because I think that

513
00:28:18,740 --> 00:28:20,500
the greatest thing our art does

514
00:28:20,500 --> 00:28:21,620
and our industry does

515
00:28:21,620 --> 00:28:23,380
is to erase the lines in the sand.

516
00:28:23,940 --> 00:28:25,780
We should continue doing that

517
00:28:25,780 --> 00:28:26,740
when the world tells us

518
00:28:26,740 --> 00:28:27,700
to make them deeper.

519
00:28:29,220 --> 00:28:31,380
While it's easy and correct

520
00:28:31,380 --> 00:28:33,140
to be dubious about the value

521
00:28:33,140 --> 00:28:34,340
of winning an Oscar,

522
00:28:34,340 --> 00:28:36,020
I do think the success of a film

523
00:28:36,020 --> 00:28:37,940
like this is a really hopeful sign

524
00:28:37,940 --> 00:28:39,300
for the future of how people

525
00:28:39,380 --> 00:28:41,140
see that which is alien to them.

526
00:28:41,140 --> 00:28:42,100
There's a philosopher

527
00:28:42,100 --> 00:28:43,300
named Julia Kristeva

528
00:28:43,300 --> 00:28:45,700
whose work was pretty formative for me.

529
00:28:45,700 --> 00:28:46,500
I discovered her

530
00:28:46,500 --> 00:28:47,700
through her being quoted

531
00:28:47,700 --> 00:28:48,980
in a series of critical essays

532
00:28:48,980 --> 00:28:49,940
on Lovecraft,

533
00:28:49,940 --> 00:28:51,300
one by Gina Whisker,

534
00:28:51,300 --> 00:28:53,460
entitled Spawn of the Pit.

535
00:28:53,460 --> 00:28:54,580
The quote went,

536
00:28:54,580 --> 00:28:56,580
By recognizing our uncanny strangeness,

537
00:28:56,580 --> 00:28:57,940
we shall neither suffer from it

538
00:28:57,940 --> 00:28:59,700
nor enjoy it from the outside.

539
00:28:59,700 --> 00:29:01,220
The foreigner is within me.

540
00:29:01,220 --> 00:29:03,140
Hence, we are all foreigners.

541
00:29:03,140 --> 00:29:04,260
If I am a foreigner,

542
00:29:04,260 --> 00:29:06,100
then there are no foreigners.

543
00:29:06,100 --> 00:29:07,700
Why be alien to each other

544
00:29:07,700 --> 00:29:10,020
when we are all alien to ourselves?

545
00:29:11,940 --> 00:29:13,460
So, what have we learned

546
00:29:13,460 --> 00:29:15,540
about how to adapt Lovecraft?

547
00:29:15,540 --> 00:29:17,300
Well, I think there's a point here

548
00:29:17,300 --> 00:29:18,900
about how we have to decide

549
00:29:18,900 --> 00:29:20,420
what really makes his work good

550
00:29:20,420 --> 00:29:21,380
in the first place,

551
00:29:21,380 --> 00:29:23,620
what the core truths in his work are

552
00:29:23,620 --> 00:29:24,660
that ought to survive

553
00:29:24,660 --> 00:29:26,100
into a future they inspire.

554
00:29:26,100 --> 00:29:27,860
An adaptation, to me at least,

555
00:29:27,860 --> 00:29:29,140
only needs fidelity

556
00:29:29,140 --> 00:29:30,260
to what really matters

557
00:29:30,260 --> 00:29:31,300
about the text,

558
00:29:31,300 --> 00:29:32,740
and neglecting to bring across

559
00:29:32,740 --> 00:29:33,940
other aspects like

560
00:29:33,940 --> 00:29:35,700
the finer points of its philosophy

561
00:29:35,700 --> 00:29:38,340
or its particular linguistic flourishes

562
00:29:38,340 --> 00:29:39,700
or certain characters

563
00:29:39,700 --> 00:29:42,260
or even its racism or homophobia

564
00:29:42,260 --> 00:29:44,260
isn't a failure to be fully faithful

565
00:29:44,260 --> 00:29:45,540
to the original work.

566
00:29:45,540 --> 00:29:46,500
It's demonstrating

567
00:29:46,500 --> 00:29:47,940
a successful understanding

568
00:29:47,940 --> 00:29:49,140
of why those stories

569
00:29:49,140 --> 00:29:50,340
were worth reading about

570
00:29:50,340 --> 00:29:51,220
in the first place

571
00:29:51,220 --> 00:29:52,660
in spite of those flaws.

572
00:29:52,660 --> 00:29:54,740
In focusing on a person's experiences

573
00:29:54,740 --> 00:29:56,340
and treatment for their sexuality

574
00:29:56,340 --> 00:29:57,380
or on a relationship

575
00:29:57,380 --> 00:29:58,820
with someone seen by others

576
00:29:58,820 --> 00:30:00,660
as an alien outsider,

577
00:30:00,660 --> 00:30:02,420
these works explore the originals

578
00:30:02,420 --> 00:30:04,340
and their feelings of otherness

579
00:30:04,420 --> 00:30:05,940
better than Lovecraft did.

580
00:30:05,940 --> 00:30:07,460
You don't have to go find a copy

581
00:30:07,460 --> 00:30:09,460
